posts.author: Steph Luciano
posts.contents: Bumped into so many friends and strangers tonight. Even along the metro we happened to form a band with 4 other strangers. They came up with Les Tigres de Metro cause of my tiger patch bomber. And no we did not sing together like a real band, we made fun of each other like real friends! It was the best time in a long time. And I highly recommend to explore LA like a local, free awesome concerts and arts brought together in one proximity? Um yes please.. literally the whole of us hysterically laughing out loud like regular obnoxious disturbances on public transportation. I feel all that laughing still in my body now üåÉüíõ thanks for listening. #losangelesiloveyou #thatsthewaylovegoes #ridingwithsteph

posts.author: ABC7 Southern California
posts.contents: @metrolosangeles is receiving nearly $1.6 billion in grants and loans to help extend the Purple Line Extension through Beverly Hills to Century City! The first phase of the extension is under construction and will run for 3.9 miles between the Wilshire/Western and Wilshire/La Cienega stations. The second phase, scheduled to be completed by 2026, will expand to Century City. The third phase, still in the planning stages, would extend the line to Westwood. @abc7brandi has the details on Eyewitness News at 5pm on ABC7 and abc7.com/live. Thanks to #abc7eyewitness @gildarake for this reflective shot from Century City!

posts.author: Stephanie Bailey (Wert)
posts.contents:
I got to eat fresh and FREE!!! Was standing in line behind an older lady who was waiting to pick up her order when a gentleman, who was with his daughter, was paying for their food and asked the lady and me what we were having. We both told our orders and he proceeded to pay for everything in full!!!! WHAT A BLESSING!!! Lord knows I wasn't feeling my best and needed that "hug from Him" to let me know everything is going to be all right! I asked who the gentleman was and all the Subway workers said, "That's Pastor Scotty from Firehouse Church! He does stuff like that all the time!!!" üòä #WhenUrLifeIsAWitness
#TrueServanthood #Subway #blessing #foodie #believer #Christ

posts.author: Discovering NYC's History
posts.contents: Columbus Circle, 1913. The west side was known to the Dutch as Bloemendaal, the ‚Äúvale of flowers.‚Äù Much of the land here was once part of the vast Somerindyck farm. Most of the area remained rural through the 1880s, with a series of small villages dotting the rocky land, such as Harsenville (centered around 70th Street and Amsterdam Avenue), Stryker‚Äôs Bay (around 97th Street and Columbus Avenue), and Carmansville (around 155th Street and Amsterdam Avenue). Development followed the path of the 9th Avenue el, which opened north of 59th Street in 1879. #TheDakota Apartments, built by Henry J. Hardenbergh in 1884, was famous for being so far away that it might as well be in the Dakota Territory (however, the developer, Edward C. Clark, had it built with the name in mind, as he wanted the surrounding streets to have Western-themed named). Clark also built middle-class housing in the area, as well as tenements, and other developers followed suit. In 1892, as part of the city‚Äôs Columbian Celebration, a group of Italian-Americans raised money for a statue that would be placed in the middle of the streets (the city also erected a temporary triumphal arch that stood on 5th Avenue and 59th Street). The column was built in 1892, and the statue, sculpted by Gaetano Russo, was put atop it in 1894. The area soon became a transportation hub, with the opening of the IRT #subway in 1904; building the tunnels under the monument without it collapsing was a major engineering feat. Dozens of trolley lines also crossed the plaza, often causing congestion and accidents. In 1905, William Eno reorganized the lines, and established the modern traffic circle. The Majestic Theatre, designed by John H. Duncan (who designed #GrantsTomb), opened in 1903. Nearby was the popular Reisenweber‚Äôs Cafe, where the Original Dixieland Jazz Band often played. In 1913, the USS Maine monument was erected, designed by Harold V. Magonigle; the bronze figures atop it were cast from guns recovered from the wreck. Interestingly, #ColumbusCircle is the place from which all distances to and from the city are measured! #NYC #architecture #entertainment #development #trivia #history #NYChistory #DiscoveringNYC

posts.author: Scot Brown
posts.contents: The Subway, or the Left Fork of North Creek makes for an amazing summer trip - it can be hiked either via the 9 mile rt "Bottom Up" hike, which does not require rappeling or via the 9.5 mile "Top Down" technical route which requires 60 feet of rope and the necessary route finding and rappeling skills to get you through the canyon... With gorgeous emerald pools, waterfalls and seeing the incredible way the water has undercut the canyon walls above you (from which the route gets its "Subway" name) - The Zion Subway is not to be missed, but be sure to wear a wetsuit on the Top Down route - that water is COLD! ‚ùÑ‚úåüèº‚ù§‚òÄüòä

posts.author: Josef Pinlac
posts.contents: A sampling of the detail in the mosaic tile art on the Chuck Close self-portrait at the 86th Street Station on the Second Avenue Subway line. Even the hairs on the beard and eyebrows are cut and inlaid individually like jewels and keep the detail of the original paintings intact. Makes me wonder why two classic portraits by him in black and white were not done this way for the station but really remarkable mosaic work. #chuckclose #selfportrait #art #tileart #mosaictiles #mosaictileart #mosaic #tiles #86thstreetstation #subwaystation #subway #mta #secondavenuesubway #2ndavenuesubway #subwayart #mtaart #nyc #newyorkcity

posts.author: Angelina Kelly
posts.contents:
Subway

I visited your restaurant today in Midlothian IL because I had the text promo for a $6 footlong. Normally I really enjoy Subway but today I do not. Not only was the staff unprofessional (a staff member pushed their family members sandwich in front of mine, even though I was the only customer) my sandwich was utterly disgusting. I got the chicken teriyaki and the chicken was shredded, which I do not remember ever being before. My bread was soggy even though I asked for it toasted. And then to top it all off it tasted like it had beans on it. In fact the chicken tasted like beans. I am very disappointed and I would like my money back. Also I will never visit this franchise again. If I want Subway I will go to another one where they know how to treat their customers.

posts.author: ABC7 Southern California
posts.contents: As a public service, we feel we need to warn you: There may be pants-less riders on your @metrolosangeles train Sunday. Never fear...it's an improv game! The phenomenon started in New York about a decade ago and takes place all around the world. It's organized here by improvisational comedy group GuerilLA. It entails wearing all your other clothes...just not your trousers...on a cold day (Sunday's L.A. forecast is 72 & partly cloudy, New York is 28 & snow), and pretend like nothing unusual is going on. If you'd like to play along, put on your best undies, grab the Metro, and meet at Union Station Sunday at 1pm. Eventually, you and your bare legs will take the Expo line and end up in Santa Monica. Details at the link in our Instagram Story. Share your pics with #abc7eyewitness! Photo: @ap.images

posts.author: New York University
posts.contents:
New York University

‚ÄúI think of New York as being in the center of the world,‚Äù says Stern sophomore Daniel de Valk, ‚Äúand with NYU right in the middle of the city, there are so many opportunities available just a subway ride away.‚Äù

For Daniel, that means it‚Äôs possible to fit in an accounting internship between his schoolwork and his part-time job as a host at a restaurant near Times Square‚Äîa balancing act that the northern California native says makes him feel like a real New Yorker. ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs amazing to be able to work in midtown alongside all these professionals, even while I‚Äôm still in school,‚Äù he says. 

Daniel says he‚Äôs only just begun to explore all that the city and the University have to offer, though he‚Äôs already made a habit of visiting museums and theaters using his NYU discount. This semester he also hopes to find time to write for Stern‚Äôs student newspaper.  

And while he misses the mountains and forests outside Sacramento, having the concrete jungle for a campus comes with its own perks: When he has downtime, Daniel likes to borrow a bike from his residence hall and ride up 6th Avenue or take a walk across one of the bridges and look back at the Manhattan skyline. For lunch between classes, nothing beats a $5 banh mi from Saigon Shack.  

‚ÄúNavigating the city, going to class, going to my internship‚Äîit‚Äôs fun,‚Äù he says, ‚Äúeven though it‚Äôs work.‚Äù

posts.author: Scot Brown
posts.contents: #TBT to one of my absolute favorite canyoneering routes in #Zion ‚Äì the Subway. This was taken the day a massive flood dumped a ton of sand into all of the beautiful, crystal clear potholes throughout the canyon... According to USGS water data, the flow rate of the North Fork of the Virgin River jumped up from 36cfs to over 800cfs that day! We made it out of the canyon okay, but it was a close call ‚Äì It's amazing how quickly nature can change a canyon through the awesome power of water and erosion; can't wait to experience the Subway again this summer! üòÅüèû‚òÄ

posts.author: Isaac thomas
posts.contents: DO YOU EVER PAY ATTENTION TO GOD'S MESSAGE??? Don't ever judge a book by its cover!!! This evening I had the honor to jump on the NYC Subway. I usually do not sit down, but I saw this one seat and decided to sit down for a couple stops. I sat down, and I look in front of me and see something non-unusual. I look up a bit, and all of a sudden I start getting goosebumps. I start making the connection between the ad and the person sitting under, and I certainly understand that this scene is not for no reason! I looked to the side, and I see everyone is busy on their phones. I'm sure no one even noticed the correlation, so obviously I have to take a picture! As the sections move along, it's obvious to me that I have to find out why I am a witness to this scenario. I decided to ride the train until this person wakes up, and I can talk to him. 30 minutes past my stop, this person jumps up ready to get off the train. I jump up and get off the train with him, and I stop him. I say, excuse me sir can I ask you a question? I continued to say, I think you're a inspiring person, can you tell me a bit about yourself??? To make a long story short, he grew up in a broken home with drugs. At a young age he understood that he is in this world for a reason. He got married at a young age and had two kids and decided to adopt three others from similar background to his own. He works 19 hours a day in order to support his extended family and provide a warm home to his own not so privileged kids. I asked him if there's anything I can do to help, he fast replied with a smile "GOD GIVES ME EVERYTHING I NEED"!!!!!! #god #inspiration #love #challenge #nyc #subway #believe #good #people #amazing #unique #angels #world #positivity #attitude

posts.contents: I literally thought this subway would never happen. For 8 years, I've heard the echo of the realtor who sold us our apt's voice saying "and when that 2nd Ave subway comes up, your apt will be worth so much more! It's such a good investment!" I used to curse that voice while commuting almost 45min to work in the village. posts.author: Gary Tatintsian Gallery
posts.contents:
Largest public art #installation in New York is on view on The Second Avenue Subway opened early in the year. Four stations present the new art from four artists including Chuck Close and Vik Muniz. 
At 86th Street, Chuck Close in ‚ÄúSubway Portraits‚Äù has created twelve large-scale works. Among them the portraits of such artists as Zhang Huan, Alex Katz, Cecily Brown, Cindy Sherman, and two distinct self-portrait

posts.author: Richard Patrick Layman
posts.contents: ~<{worldy friends}>~ With the loss of one of my "best friends", I was greeted with Francesco. I had known Phil (right) for 3 years on instagram when we met in person this weekend. He introduced me to his partner who came into his life about the same time I did. Francesco shocked me. I never expected an impact such as he to come into my life. Phil shocked me as well. I felt close to him before we met, but this past week has shaken my life in the best way possible. It's funny how life works I guess. I miss them terribly since they've gone and it's only been a couple of days. This is my absolute favorite picture of them that I had taken. ‚ù§Ô∏è Love you guys! posts.author: FACTGASM
posts.contents:
According to the color theory, Red, Orange, yellow or such striking colors are known to subconsciously trigger hunger and/or induce excitement. These colors make guests to spend more and leave at the earliest‚Äì which is exactly what fast food restaurants want you to do. Research has shown that people eat more in a room with warm color surroundings as opposed to consuming food in a room painted in cold colors such as blue, black, or purple.
Source: famouslogos.org

posts.author: American Experience
posts.contents:
(1/2) Our upcoming doc The Race Underground chronicles the building of America's first subway system in Boston, otherwise known as the ‚ÄúT.‚Äù The film is based on the book of the same name by reporter Doug Most, pictured here at Arlington Street Station.
"It‚Äôs technically not the first subway stop, because this station was aboveground,‚Äù says Most. ‚ÄúIt was, however, the spot where a streetcar descended underground for the first time, stopping, on the morning of September 1, 1897, at the crest of the hill at Arlington Street."
üöáüöÉ
Ride the T back in time with Doug Most, on the route of America's first subway in Boston, MA, and tune in to @PBS on January 31 for the premiere of #RaceUndergroundPBS.
.
.
.
#americanexperience #documentary #boston #mbta #subway #igersboston
